      "Based on my web search, I found several AI coding agents and related products featured on Product Hunt in February 2026. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Notable AI Coding Agents from February 2026\n\n### 1. **Base44** (February 17)\n- A complete backend service designed for building AI agent applications\n- Optimized specifically for **Claude Code** and Cursor\n- Tested on millions of real-world applications\n- Deploy full-stack applications with a single command: `npx base44@latest create`\n- Eliminates backend setup and configuration\n- Uses simple skills rather than complex APIs\n\n### 2. **Blink Agent Builder** (January/February)\n- Marketed as the \"first full-stack vibe coding platform built specifically for Agents\"\n- Users describe their desired agent in natural language\n- Automatically builds frontend, backend, and agent logic\n- Includes built-in web search, code execution, vector database, and sandbox environment\n- Supports 180+ AI models\n- Claims to have rebuilt Cursor, Perplexity, and Shortcut in minutes\n\n### 3. **Mastra**\n- Modern TypeScript AI Agent framework\n- Includes workflow orchestration, memory management, streaming output, evaluations, link tracing\n- Features a visual Studio for development\n- Allows using the same stack from prototype to production\n\n### 4. **Forge Agent** (January 24)\n- Focuses on PyTorch optimization\n- Features CUDA kernels and Triton kernels\n- Supports AI agent parallel computing and model acceleration\n\n### 5. **Tonkotsu** (January 23)\n- Programming agent with team management and interface design features\n- Document management capabilities\n- Free trial available\n\n### Additional Context from Hacker News (February 8, 2026):\n- The search results mention a discussion about **\"Ask HN: What are you working on?\"** where developers were showcasing how AI writes code for them\n- Mentioned tools include **Claude Code**, **Opus 4.6**, and various AI agents\n- **Prompter Hawk** was highlighted - a task scheduling dashboard for AI agents with features like parallel session monitoring, cost analysis, automatic retry, and Mermaid architecture diagram generation\n- One notable example: a developer spent $65 for Opus 4.6 to write a Bambu 3D printer alternative client\n\nThe trend in February 2026 shows AI coding agents becoming increasingly sophisticated, with platforms emerging that specialize in agent development (\"vibe coding\"), backend infrastructure for AI applications, and specialized frameworks for TypeScript-based agent development."
